e)</i> ‘rook’ + <i>wod(e)</i> ‘wood’ (Old English <i>hrōc</i>, <i>wudu</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Rookewood was born in 1393, in Illington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William De Rookewood, was 22 and his mother, Agnes Thorpe, was 13. He married Elizabeth Tyrell in 1424, in Euston, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in Euston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1393–":"1393–Surnud","1393–Male":"1393–Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1427–1482":"1427–1482","1440–1521":"1440–1521","1371–1422":"1371–1422","1424":"1424","1422":"1422","1521":"1521","1387":"1387","Abt 1440":"umbes 1440","1440":"1440","1482":"1482","1393":"1393","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1427":"1427","Illington, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Illington, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanfield, Breckland, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stanfield, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Euston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Euston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fishley, Euston, Suffolk, England":"Euston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1393–":"1393–Kuollut","1393–Male":"1393–Kuollut","1387–